# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annegret-kramp-karrenbauer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 1998 to elect the members of the 14th Bundestag.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest faction in parliament for the first time since 1972, with its leader Gerhard Schröder becoming chancellor.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The Christian Democrats had their worst election result since 1949.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Since German reunification on 3 October 1990, the unemployment rate in Germany had risen from 4.2% to 9.4% in 1998, with the Federal Labor Office registering more than 4 million unemployed.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The unified Germany had to fight economic and domestic difficulties even as it actively participated in the project of European integration.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Most people blamed the centre-right coalition government of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union (CDU/CSU) and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) for the economic difficulties.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Longtime Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government was regarded by many as not having fully implemented the unification after eight years, in view of the mass protests in many eastern German towns due to job losses and social welfare cuts.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 campaign began with both the CDU and SPD working out who would lead their parties.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] There had been rumours that Kohl would resign and allow Wolfgang Schäuble to take the reins of the CDU, but these rumours were rendered obsolete when Kohl announced in April 1997 that he would seek the chancellorship for a sixth term.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The two contenders for the SPD nomination were Oskar Lafontaine, the party's chairman, and Gerhard Schröder, Minister-President of Lower Saxony.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] On 1 March 1998, Schröder led the SPD to a huge victory in the Lower Saxony state election, gaining an unusual absolute majority for the second time and effectively receiving the SPD nomination for federal chancellor.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder had announced he would withdraw his bid for the nomination if he received below 42 percent of the popular vote.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] In the 1998 general elections, Schröder received 47.9 percent.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Following this election, Lafontaine withdrew his bid and Schröder was inaugurated in the May 1998 convention.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] For the SPD, Schröder offered a new face for the party.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] He gave the party a new vigor, one that was lacking in the CDU after Kohl proclaimed his nomination.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the CDU questioned if Kohl had made the right choice for the party.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU campaign was based on the experience and reputation of Kohl.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] One of the CDU's main slogans was 'Safety, not Risks.' "Kohl exploited his familiarity and experience, as well as his status as Europe's longest serving head of government." The SPD on the other hand ran the campaign using strategies developed in the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD set up election headquarters and introduced 'rapid rebuttal units' not unlike those used by Bill Clinton of the United States in his successful presidential bid in 1992.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD avoided direct attacks at Kohl, but rather focused on their message of a "new center".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP had usually ridden on the coattails of the CDU, and was mostly disapproved in the polls.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] With the SPD well ahead in the polls, many of the voters from the CDU had fewer incentives to vote for the FDP.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP was also having trouble projecting a coherent platform to voters.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The Greens too were having issues concerning their platform.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The two factions in the Greens, the fundamentalists and the pragmatists, had problems settling on their platform since the founding of the Green party.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The major issue of the 1998 campaign was unemployment.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] In 1996, the unemployment rate in Germany surpassed the government's "limit" of 4 million unemployed people.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Both parties blamed high labor costs, high taxes and the high welfare costs as the causes of the problem.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] During the campaign, Schröder used this issue against Kohl, calling him 'the unemployment chancellor.' Unemployment was worst in the former East Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] While the national rate stood at 9.4 percent, former East Germany was suffering with unemployment at 20 percent.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the former East Germany blamed Kohl for the slow economic recovery.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Another issue at hand were Germany's tax and welfare reforms.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] While the CDU/CSU had offered proposals to reduce benefits in healthcare and pensions, the SPD controlled Bundesrat secured the passage of the bill.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The proposed bill also offered tax cuts that were to benefit the rich, something the SPD opposed.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] While Kohl continually pushed the issue of European integration, the issue fell short from voters' minds.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder, on the other hand, almost ignored the issue.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Many voters in Germany had other concerns besides the European Union.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Toward the end of the campaign, polls placed the CDU/CSU and FDP coalition in a tie with the SPD and Green coalition.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Despite these polls, the final numbers told a different story.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD-Green coalition won an unexpectedly large victory, taking 345 seats and earning a strong majority in the Bundestag—the first centre-left absolute majority in post-World War II Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD won 40.9 percent of the vote, due to an increase of 4.5 percent from 1994.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU-FDP coalition had gone into the election with a solid majority and 341 seats, but was cut down to 288 seats.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU lost 6.2% of its 1994 vote, and lost 109 electoral districts to the SPD.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Germany's mixed-member proportional system, in which a slate of statewide delegates are elected alongside the electorate delegates, softened the blow somewhat, so the CDU/CSU only suffered a net loss of 49 seats.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] It was still the CDU/CSU's worst defeat ever.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] By contrast, their junior coalition partner, the FDP, netted a loss of just 4 seats.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg, Saxony-Anhalt, Saarland, Bremen, Hamburg and (for the first and last time) Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl lost his own constituency of Ludwigshafen, though he was still re-elected to the Bundestag through the Rhineland-Palatinate CDU party list, and he had not won the seat in the 1983 and 1987 elections.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Future Chancellor Angela Merkel only narrowly won her constituency of Stralsund – Rügen – Grimmen with only 37.3 percent of the vote; the only time she got less than 40 percent of the vote.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] A new government was formed by a coalition between the SPD and the Greens, with the SPD's Gerhard Schröder as chancellor and Greens leader Joschka Fischer as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] It was the first red-green coalition government at the federal level in Germany, as well as the first purely centre-left government in post-World War II Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl stepped down as chairman of the CDU, as did CSU chairman Theodor Waigel.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 German election was historic in many ways.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] It resulted in a centre-right government being succeeded by a left-wing one—the first in postwar Germany (the SPD's previous term in government had been at the helm of a centre-left coalition).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] In addition, it brought to an end the sixteen-year rule of Kohl – the second-longest of any German chancellor, and the longest tenure for a democratically elected head of government in German history.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] It has been compared to the defeat of Winston Churchill in 1945 – both were seen as conservative wartime leaders, and in both cases both were turned out of office by the electorate once the war was over.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1998-german-federal-election] Churchill was ousted before World War II was even over, while Kohl managed to hang onto power for two more terms after the reunification of Germany (which is often considered to be the end of the Cold War).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1999-saarland-state-election] The **1999 Saarland state election** was held on 5 September 1999 to elect the members of the Landtag of Saarland.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1999-saarland-state-election] The incumbent Social Democratic Party (SPD) government led by Minister-President Reinhard Klimmt was defeated.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1999-saarland-state-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU) won a narrow majority of one seat.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1999-saarland-state-election] CDU leader Peter Müller was subsequently elected minister-president.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/1999-saarland-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the previous Landtag of Saarland.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2004-saarland-state-election] The **2004 Saarland state election** was held on 5 September 2004 to elect the members of the Landtag of Saarland.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2004-saarland-state-election] The incumbent Christian Democratic Union (CDU) government led by Minister-President Peter Müller retained its majority and continued in office.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 2009 to elect the members of the 17th Bundestag.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU), its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) won the election, and the three parties formed a new centre-right government with Angela Merkel as chancellor.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] While CDU/CSU's share of votes decreased slightly, it was more than compensated by the gains of their "desired coalition partner", the liberal FDP, that won the strongest result in its history.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] CDU and CSU's former partner in the "Grand coalition", the Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Frank-Walter Steinmeier, conceded defeat after dropping by more than 11 percentage points, receiving its hitherto worst result since the end of the Second World War (only undercut in 2017 and 2025).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] At 70.8 percent, the voter turnout was the lowest in a German federal election since 1949.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Since the 2005 election, Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) had governed in a grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] However, it was her stated goal to win a majority for CDU/CSU and FDP (the CDU/CSU's traditional coalition partner) in 2009.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Foreign minister and Vice-Chancellor Frank-Walter Steinmeier (SPD) was formally nominated as his party's chancellor-candidate at a convention on 18 October 2008.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] He aimed to form a government in which the SPD was the strongest party, but which also excluded the left-socialist party The Left.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The election campaign was considered exceptionally boring, which may be attributable to a perceived lack of charisma on the part of the leaders of the CDU and SPD.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Another reason pointed to for the sedate campaign is that the CDU and SPD both defended the record of their grand coalition, and facing the possibility of having to continue the grand coalition in a friendly manner.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Merkel was content with the low-key campaign style, which was largely seen as benefiting her party because of her high approval ratings.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] CDU candidate Vera Lengsfeld released a campaign poster featuring herself and Merkel in a way that emphasised their cleavage.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The poster bore the slogan "We have more to offer" (German: "*Wir haben mehr zu bieten*").
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] On 23 September 2009, four days before the federal elections, German police raided the Berlin headquarters of the National Democratic Party of Germany NPD to investigate claims that letters sent from the NPD to politicians from immigrant backgrounds incited racial hatred.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The federal election was the final and most important election in what is called a *Superwahljahr* (super election year) in Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU and FDP, with an average vote share of around 50% in pre-election polling during the weeks before the election, were clearly ahead of the other traditional coalition partners in Germany, SPD and the Greens.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU received a slightly lower proportion than in the previous election, with the Bavarian CSU receiving its lowest vote share in decades.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Overall, the CDU/CSU had their worst vote share in 60 years.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] In contrast, their preferred coalition partner, the liberal FDP, gained nearly 5% points to give it 14.6% of the vote, the best result of its history.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The big loser of the election was the SPD, which received its worst result ever in a federal election, receiving only 23% of the total party vote and suffering the biggest percentage loss of any party in German federal election history in 60 years.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] The two other parties represented in the Bundestag, the Left and the Greens, both made large gains and received the highest vote share of their respective histories.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] For the first time, The Left won constituency seats outside its traditional stronghold of East Berlin.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] As a result of the losses by the SPD and the gains by the FDP, the alliance of the CDU/CSU and FDP received an outright majority of seats, ensuring that Angela Merkel would continue as chancellor.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] Had the CDU/CSU and FDP failed to win a majority of seats, possible alternative coalitions may have included a continuation of the grand coalition of CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2009-german-federal-election] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was specifically ruled out by FDP leader Guido Westerwelle.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The **2011 FIFA Women's World Cup** was the sixth FIFA Women's World Cup competition, the world championship for women's national football teams.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It was held from 26 June to 17 July 2011 in Germany, which won the right to host the event in October 2007.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Japan won the final against the United States on a penalty shoot-out following a 2–2 draw after extra time and became the first Asian team to win a senior FIFA World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The matches were played in nine stadiums in nine host cities around the country, with the final played at the Commerzbank Arena in Frankfurt.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Sixteen teams were selected for participation via a worldwide qualification tournament that began in 2009.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the first round of the tournament finals, the teams competed in round-robin groups of four teams for points, with the top two teams in each group proceeding.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] These eight teams advanced to the knockout stage, where two rounds of play decided which teams would participate in the final.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The hosts and defending champions Germany were eliminated by Japan in the quarterfinals with a 1-0 result in extra time.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Six nations, Australia, Canada, France, Germany, Peru and Switzerland, initially declared their interest in hosting the 2011 Women's World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The German Football Association announced its hopes to host the tournament on 26 January 2006, following a pledge from German Chancellor Angela Merkel to fully support a potential bid.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] All six nations officially announced their interest by a 1 March 2007 deadline and acknowledged their intention of bidding by 3 May 2007 to FIFA.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The final bidding dossiers had to be handed over before 1 August 2007.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Switzerland withdrew on 29 May 2007, stating that Europe is heavily focused on France and Germany, and a third European bid appeared futile.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 27 August 2007, France also withdrew, reportedly in exchange for Germany's support for their bid to host the men's UEFA Euro 2016.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Later Australia (12 October 2007) and Peru (17 October 2007) voluntarily dropped out of the race as well, leaving only Canada and Germany as the remaining candidates.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 30 October 2007, the FIFA Executive Committee voted to assign the tournament to Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Canada was eventually awarded the 2015 Women's World Cup four years later.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Upon the selection, Germany became the third country to host both men's and women's World Cup, having hosted the men's twice in 1974 and 2006.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] After the German Football Association (DFB) expressed its intention to bid for the Women's World Cup, 23 German cities applied to host World Cup games.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Twelve cities were chosen for the official bidding dossier handed over to FIFA in August 2007.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 30 September 2008, the DFB executive committee decided to use nine stadiums for the tournament; the original candidates Essen, Magdeburg and Bielefeld were not chosen as World Cup venues.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The official opening game was held between Germany and Canada at the Olympic Stadium in Berlin, the venue of the 2006 men's World Cup final; it was the only match played in Berlin.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] However, it was not the first match of the tournament—it was preceded by a match at Rhein-Neckar-Arena in Sinsheim pitting France and Nigeria.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The final of the tournament took place at the Commerzbank-Arena in Frankfurt, the venue of the 2005 men's Confederations Cup final.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Borussia-Park in Mönchengladbach and Frankfurt's Commerzbank-Arena hosted the semi-finals.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The third place play-off was held at Rhein-Neckar-Arena.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Since 2007, five of the stadiums were either newly built (Augsburg, Dresden and Sinsheim) or remodelled (Bochum and Leverkusen).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Six stadiums would be home grounds for German First Bundesliga clubs in the upcoming 2011–12 season, while the other three would be home to Second Bundesliga clubs in the same season.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Compared to the 2006 men's World Cup, several smaller venues were chosen; six stadiums have a capacity of 20,000 to 30,000 seats.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] All cities would stage a total of four matches, with the exceptions of Berlin and Mönchengladbach; the latter would host three games.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The total capacity of the nine venues is roughly 330,000.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Overall, approximately one million tickets would be available.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Several of the stadiums were officially referred to simply as "FIFA Women's World Cup Stadium" because FIFA prohibited sponsorship of stadiums unless the stadium sponsors were also official tournament sponsors.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] With no standing-room terraces allowed, all stadiums had a lower total capacity compared to German Bundesliga games.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA had considered the prospect of increasing the number of teams from 16 to 24, to reflect the growing global popularity of women's football and the Women's World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] However, on 14 March 2008, the FIFA Executive Committee decided to keep the number of participants at 16, concerned that more teams would dilute the quality of play.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The idea of having 20 teams taking part, which had been discussed briefly, was ruled impossible to implement in terms of fixture planning and logistics.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] During the 2007 Women's World Cup, FIFA president Sepp Blatter had campaigned for the idea to increase the number of teams, although this proposal was not unquestioned.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In particular the 11–0 victory of Germany over Argentina in the opening game of the 2007 tournament had caused a debate over whether there were 24 national teams on a comparable level.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In October 2008, the FIFA Executive Committee announced a change to the allocation of the qualifying berths for its continental confederations.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Asia was granted 3 automatic berths instead of 2.5 for the finals (although in 2007 the host nation was an additional qualifier from Asia).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Europe's allocation was reduced from 5 to 4.5 (although it effectively increased to 5.5 because of the automatic qualification of the host nation).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The North/Central American and Caribbean confederation (CONCACAF) retained their 2.5 qualifiers, Africa and South America 2 each, and Oceania 1.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The 16th qualifying spot was determined through a play-off between the third-placed team in CONCACAF and the winner of repechage play-offs in Europe.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA also ruled that each confederation has to ensure that at least one third of its member associations enter their women's national teams for World Cup qualification, otherwise FIFA would re-examine the current slot allocation.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In Africa and the Middle East a considerable percentage of teams had withdrawn from World Cup qualification in the past.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For European teams, the 2011 Women's World Cup was also used as a qualification tournament for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Besides Team Great Britain, Europe had two additional qualifiers for the Summer Olympics.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] With Germany losing their quarter-final, France, which had already reached the semi-finals, secured qualification to the Olympics.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Sweden followed as UEFA's second team with its win against Australia.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Qualification for the tournament took place between April 2009 and November 2010.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] As the host nation, Germany were granted automatic qualification, while the remaining national teams qualified through their continental confederations.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Most confederations used their continental championship tournaments – the AFC Women's Asian Cup, CAF Women's Championship, OFC Women's Championship, Sudamericano Femenino and CONCACAF Women's Gold Cup – to determine qualification.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The exception to this was UEFA, which used its own qualifying tournament.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] One qualification spot was determined by a play-off between a UEFA and CONCACAF team.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Colombia and Equatorial Guinea made their debuts in the FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Brazil, Germany, Japan, Nigeria, Norway, Sweden and the United States maintained their streak of qualifying for all six tournaments so far, while China PR failed to qualify for the first time ever.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] This is Mexico's first appearance since 1999 and France's first appearance since 2003.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament is supervised by the "Women's World Cup 2011 Organising Committee Germany".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] President of the Organising Committee (OC) is former German international Steffi Jones; she started her work on 1 January 2008.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] German president Christian Wulff was named the patron of the tournament.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The Organising Committee is chaired by Jones and supervised by the board of the German Football Federation (DFB).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 January 2009, Jones opened the committee offices and named her OC team.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It is led by managing director Uli Wolter, who headed the Leipzig branch during the 2006 men's World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Aside from Wolter, four department heads were named.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Intended to advertise the tournament primarily in Germany, the Organising Committee named four national Women's World Cup ambassadors: former German internationals Britta Carlson, Renate Lingor, and Sandra Minnert, as well as shooting Paralympics gold medallist Manuela Schmermund.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In October 2009, former U.S. international Mia Hamm was presented as the World Cup's international ambassador.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each host city except for Berlin also named two city ambassadors.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] They include footballers Matthias Sammer, Karl-Heinz Riedle and Rainer Bonhof, fencer Britta Heidemann or biathlete Magdalena Neuner.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The official World Cup emblem, called Arena Deutschland, was presented by Steffi Jones and Franz Beckenbauer in the break between the women's and the men's game of the German Cup final on 19 April 2008.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It shows a stylised stadium with stripes in the national colours of Germany, black, red and gold, and a pictogram of the Women's World Cup trophy in the upper right corner.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It was designed by the Stuttgart advertising agency WVP.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament mascot, cat "Karla Kick", was presented during the opening game of the 2010 Under-20 Women's World Cup on 13 July 2010.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The mascot was developed by the Frankfurt agency GMR Marketing.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] According to Jones, the mascot represents "important attributes of women's football: passion, fun and dynamics".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Approximately one million tickets were available in total, with 900,000 on general sale.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] 350,000 tickets were offered at discount prices, mainly intended for families, clubs and schools, one of the key target groups of the Organising Committee.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The World Cup tickets were offered in several sales phases.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] During the first sales period from 29 October 2009 to 31 August 2010, only so-called city series tickets were offered.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each city series includes tickets for all games of that particular host city.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the second sales period from 17 February to 31 August 2010, so-called 20Eleven tickets were sold to groups of at least 11 people, offered at a 20 percent discount and directed primarily at schools and clubs.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Single tickets for all matches were first sold starting 15 September 2010.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The prices of individual tickets range from €10 to €200.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 18 March 2011, 100 days before the opening game, the last sales phase started, with all remaining tickets being sold in the order in which orders are received.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Unlike tickets at the 2006 men's World Cup in Germany, the tickets for the Women's World Cup were not personalised.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The same city series ticket can be used by different people for different games.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament's budget has been set at €51 million.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The German Football Association plans to cover these costs in almost equal parts from ticket sales and from sponsors, primarily from six so-called National Supporters.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In order for the tournament to break even, the DFB has said about 80% of the tickets need to be sold, which would translate to an average attendance of 25,000.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The DFB estimates to earn roughly €27 million through the general ticket sale.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] From 2008 to 2010, the six National Supporters were presented: the tele-communications company Deutsche Telekom, the bank Commerzbank, the insurer Allianz, the retailer Rewe, the national mail company Deutsche Post and the national railway company Deutsche Bahn.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Aside from Deutsche Bahn, the sponsors are identical with those of the 2010 U-20 Women's World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The television coverage of the tournament was unprecedented.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For the first time, all matches were produced in high definition, with in-goal cameras and two steadicams being used for all matches.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For selected matches, the broadcast production comprised up to 18 cameras, including a spidercam and a helicopter camera.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In Germany the public broadcasters ARD and ZDF showed all 32 tournament games live.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Across Europe, all games were available on Eurosport in 34 countries and territories.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the United States, ESPN and ESPN2 served as the official English-language broadcaster, while Univision carried coverage in Spanish.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In Canada, CBC Television and Sportsnet broadcast the tournament; the event was the first in a sub-licensing partnership for FIFA tournaments between the two networks.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the United Kingdom, the games of the England national team were shown live by BBC Red Button and the BBC Sport website.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] SBS held the broadcasting rights for Australia, while Al Jazeera broadcast matches in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was the first women's event to be the subject of a Panini sticker album, available only in Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The final match between Japan and the United States broke the record for most tweets per second on Twitter – 7,196.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA's Referees' Committee selected 16 referees to officiate at the World Cup: three from the AFC, one from the CAF, two from CONMEBOL, three from CONCACAF, one from the OFC and six from UEFA.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In addition 32 assistant referees and three fourth officials were selected.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The oldest referee was 42-year-old Swede Jenny Palmquist, while the youngest referee was 29-year-old Finau Vulvuli of Fiji.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] As with the 2007 tournament, each team's squad for the 2011 Women's World Cup consisted of 21 players, two less than men's World Cup squads.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each participating national association had to confirm their final 21-player squad no later than 10 working days before the start of the tournament.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Replacement of seriously injured players was permitted until 24 hours before the team in question's first World Cup game.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 June 2011 the A sample of Yineth Varón, goalkeeper of Colombia, tested positive to an as yet unknown substance.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] She was provisionally suspended by the FIFA until the B sample result was known.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 August 2011, it was confirmed that she had received a two-year ban.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 7 July 2011, FIFA announced that two players from North Korea, Song Jong-Sun and Jong Pok-Sim, were provisionally suspended prior to their team's match against Colombia after failing doping tests during the tournament.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 16 July, FIFA announced that three additional players (Hong Myong-Hui, Ho Un-Byol and Ri Un-Hyang) from North Korea tested positive following target testing of the whole team.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 August 2011, the Korean team was fined US$400,000, which is equal to the prize it received by finishing 13th in the 2011 tournament, and was excluded from participation at the 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The Organising Committee approved the procedure for the final draw on 28 November 2010.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Four teams from different geographic regions – Germany, Japan, United States, Brazil – were seeded based on their FIFA Women's World Rankings.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] No two teams from the same confederation were to be drawn in the same group, with the exception of Group A, which would include two European teams.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The group draw was staged in Frankfurt, Germany, on 29 November 2010 at the Congress Centrum.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The ceremony was presented by Organising Committee president Steffi Jones, assisted by FIFA Head of Women's Competitions Tatjana Haenni.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The balls were drawn by former German international Günter Netzer and Slovak model and women's football ambassador Adriana Karembeu.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Group A was the group of death of this FIFA World Cup with three top 10-ranked teams: Germany (2), Canada (6) and France (7).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The first round, or group stage, sees the sixteen teams divided into four groups of four teams.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each group is a round-robin of six games, where each team plays one match against each of the other teams in the same group.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Teams are awarded three points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The teams finishing first and second in each group qualifies for the quarter-finals.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The match schedule for the tournament was released on 20 March 2009, with the hosts placed in position A1.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Unlike previous Women's World Cup final tournaments, there were no double-headers, but matches on the same day were held in different venues.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] According to the Organising Committee, this "signals the increased quality and status of the women's finals".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The knockout stage comprised the eight teams that advanced from the group stage of the tournament.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There were three rounds of matches, with each round eliminating half of the teams entering that round.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The successive rounds were the quarter-finals, semi-finals, and the final.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There is also a play-off to decide third and fourth place.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For each game in the knockout stage, any draw at 90 minutes was followed by thirty minutes of extra time; if scores were still level, there would be a penalty shootout to determine who progressed to the next round.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The following awards were given at the conclusion of the tournament.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The Golden Ball (best overall player), Golden Boot (top scorer) and Golden Glove (best goalkeeper) awards were sponsored by Adidas, while the Best Young Player award was sponsored by Hyundai Motor Company.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA.com shortlisted ten goals for users to vote on as the Goal of the Tournament, which was sponsored by Sony.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There were 86 goals scored in 32 matches, for an average of 2.69 goals per match.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Homare Sawa of Japan won the Golden Boot award for scoring five goals.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Aya Miyama of Japan won the assists table with four assists.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Per statistical convention in football, matches decided in extra time are counted as wins and losses, while matches decided by penalty shoot-outs are counted as draws.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In June 2023, Nilla Fischer revealed in her book, *I Didn't Even Say Half Of It*, that the Swedish team were told to show their genitalia to prove that they were women during the 2011 competition.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] This came after protests from Nigeria, South Africa and Ghana relating to allegations that the Equatorial Guinea squad included men.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Fischer described the process, which was conducted by a female physiotherapist on behalf of the doctor, as humiliating but did not have a choice in order to not jeopardise the opportunity to play at a World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA said it had taken note of recent comments made by Nilla Fischer around her experiences and gender verification testing conducted by the Swedish national team at the World Cup.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] The **2012 Saarland state election** was held in on 25 March 2012 to elect the members of the Landtag of Saarland.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] The election was triggered by the collapse of the previous coalition government comprising the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) led by Minister-President Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, Free Democratic Party (FDP), and The Greens.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] The CDU subsequently formed a grand coalition with the Social Democratic Party (SPD), and Kramp-Karrenbauer was re-elected as Minister-President.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] After the 2009 state election, a Jamaica coalition (CDU–FDP–Green) government took office, the first of its kind in Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] The government collapsed on 6 January 2012 due to internal issues in the FDP.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] Minister-President Kramp-Karrenbauer stated that "[a] credible and reliable cooperation is no longer completely possible in this coalition." The CDU held discussions with the Social Democratic Party in an attempt to form a grand coalition, but this failed, causing early elections to be called.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] Having been reelected as the largest party in the Landtag, CDU was tasked with forming the government.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] Minister-President Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer said that she was seeking to form a grand coalition with the SPD, which have 37 seats altogether.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] Both parties reached a coalition agreement on 24 April 2012.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] The CDU and SPD would control 3 ministries each.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] Kramp-Karrenbauer will also head the new government which will be sworn on 9 May 2012.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] On 9 May 2012 Kramp-Karrenbauer's new government gained the vote of confidence with 37 votes.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] There was 12 votes against and 2 abstentions.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2012-saarland-state-election] Her cabinet was later endorsed by the Landtag with the same number of votes.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] A federal election was held on 22 September to elect the members of the 18th Bundestag of Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] At stake were all 598 seats to the Bundestag, plus 33 overhang seats determined thereafter.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union of Germany/Christian Social Union of Bavaria (CDU/CSU) of incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel won their best result since 1990 with nearly 42% of the vote and nearly 50% of the seats, just five short for an overall majority.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The co-governing Free Democratic Party (FDP) failed to meet the 5% vote electoral threshold in what was their worst showing ever in a federal election at the time, the electoral wipeout denying them seats in the Bundestag for the first time in their history.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU's narrowly missed a majority, and the FDP failed to get any seats, any prospective government was required to be a new coalition.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The only possible coalition government excluding the CDU/CSU would have been an all-left-wing red–red–green coalition, since a red–green alliance, similar to the German government between 1998 and 2005, would not have enough seats for a majority.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Both the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) and Alliance 90/The Greens ruled out governing with The Left that had ruled former East Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Ultimately, Merkel's party reached a coalition agreement with the then-main opposition party, the SPD, to form another grand coalition, the third in the country's history since World War II.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The SPD leadership conducted a ratification vote by their broader membership before the agreement was made final.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] This grand coalition was renewed after the 2017 German federal election due to failure during the negotiations of a Jamaica coalition.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The date of the federal election is governed by the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (Germany's constitution) and the Federal Election Law (*Bundeswahlgesetz*).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Article 39 of the Basic Law states that the Bundestag shall be elected between 46 and 48 months after the beginning of the legislative period.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] As the 17th Bundestag convened on 27 October 2009, the election was scheduled between 27 August and 27 October 2013.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] To avoid school holidays, a date in late September is usually chosen; this made 15 or 22 September 2013 the most likely dates.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The President of Germany ordered 22 September 2013 to be the election day upon the recommendation of the federal government.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Polling stations were open from 8:00 to 18:00.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Although the chancellor-candidates (*Kanzlerkandidaten*) play a very important role in election campaigns, their office is not regulated in any law, and it is up to each party to determine how, and if at all, to name a chancellor-candidate.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The SPD names a chancellor-candidate, while the CDU and the CSU name a common one.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The smaller Bundestag parties (the FDP, the Left, and the Greens) usually do not name a chancellor-candidate as it is very improbable for such a candidate to actually be elected chancellor.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] They instead name one or two persons (*Spitzenkandidaten*) who are to become the faces of that party's campaign.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] While a sitting chancellor is usually named chancellor-candidate for his or her own party, the main opposition party's process to determine their chancellor-candidate differs.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Most times, such a person is determined in an inner party circle and then anointed in a party convention.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU is the main government party, CDU chairwoman and incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel was not challenged as chancellor-candidate.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] In the SPD, the situation was a bit less clear, as there were four candidates in the discussion.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Gabriel, Steinmeier, and Steinbrück all had a bad electoral record, as they all had led their party into painful defeats in state or general elections.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Gabriel and Steinbrück lost their inherited minister-president offices in 2003 and 2005, and Steinmeier failed as a chancellor-candidate in 2009.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] On 28 September 2012, the party announced that Steinbrück would be the SPD's chancellor-candidate.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] After taking heat domestically for bailing out other European countries, Finance-Minister Wolfgang Schäuble took the step of mentioning that Greece would need a third bailout.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] This was in stark contrast to his colleagues who had refrained from making such measures in light of the election, in particularly following Merkel's dismissal of a potential future bailout.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] In reaction to the statement and the dithering, Peer Steinbrueck of the SPD said that it was "time that Mrs.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Merkel tells people the truth", while Jürgen Trittin of the Greens also criticized Merkel.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Her visit was welcomed by residents of the town due to its historic nature but was also suggested as a vote ploy ahead of the election.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] She also campaigned on Germany's unemployment record that fell to a two-decade low during her premiership, progress towards a balanced budget, and the Eurozone's advantages for Germany's exports.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] There were questions asked about her legacy and a potential heir to the party leadership.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Campaigning in the "hot phase" ended on 21 September, as Merkel appealed to voters to support her against Eurosceptics.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] A 90-minute televised debate between the lead candidates of the CDU/CSU and the SPD, the two leading contenders, was held on 1 September.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The smaller-party top-ranking candidates Rainer Brüderle (FDP), Jürgen Trittin (Alliance 90/The Greens), and Gregor Gysi (The Left) held a separate debate on 2 September.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] In Germany, there are regular opinion polls during the whole of the legislative period.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Germany's major polling agencies are Allensbach, Emnid, Forsa, Forschungsgruppe Wahlen, GMS, Infratest dimap, and INSA/YouGov.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] August 2013 opinion polls suggested that the CDU/CSU and the FDP (black–yellow coalition) would be just short of or just above an absolute majority, rather than the SPD and Greens (red–green coalition), partners in Gerhard Schröder-led government (1998–2005).
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Only four parties were present in the Bundestag for the first time since the 1987 West German federal election, as the CDU/CSU operates as one Bundestag group.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU) and the Christian Social Union of Bavaria (CSU) scored 42 percent of the vote, their best result since tallying 44% in 1990.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Since 15.7 percent of the vote went to parties that fell short of the 5% electoral threshold, the CDU/CSU came up just five seats short of a majority.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP), junior partner in the outgoing coalition government, failed to pass the 5% threshold.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] It also failed to win any directly elected seats, as it has not won any directly elected seats since 1990, shutting it out of the Bundestag altogether for the first time in the party's history.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] A new Eurosceptic party, Alternative for Germany, nearly won seats but was shut out by narrowly missing the 5% electoral threshold.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Below are second votes (*Zweitstimme*, or votes for party list), by state.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel said: "It was a strong vote to take responsibility in Germany, but also in Europe and the world." Peer Steinbrück announced his withdrawal from top politics and his intention to focus on his ordinary tasks as a member of parliament.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] As in the red-baiting and Red Scare campaign ("red socks") during the 1994 German federal election, Merkel scared off that the alternative was a left-wing red–red–green coalition government, since the FDP lost all its seats.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Many SPD insiders did not want to work with The Left.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] One day after the election, Merkel announced that she had already spoken with the SPD but would not rule out other possibilities.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The Greens were open to coalition talks with the CDU/CSU, but CSU leaders said they opposed a coalition with the Greens.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The Greens announced they would not consider going into coalition with the Left.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Formal talks began in the first week of October when Merkel met SPD leaders on 4 October.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] She said: "Europe is watching us, the world is watching us.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] We have the common responsibility to build a stable government." She also planned to hold talks with the Greens the following week.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] After five weeks of negotiations that culminated in an all-night session 27–28 November, the CDU/CSU reached agreement with the SPD to form a new coalition government.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] Issues resolved in the talks included the planned introduction of a minimum hourly wage of €8.50 in 2015 and no new taxes.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The deal depended on approval by the SPD rank and file, with a poll set for 6 December.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] On 14 December, 76% of the SPD's members voted for the coalition to go ahead.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] The Third Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 17 December.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/2013-german-federal-election] This grand coalition continued after the 2017 German federal election.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In February 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer announced that she would resign her position as CDU leader later in the year and would not put herself forward as a candidate for chancellor for the 2021 federal election.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was succeeded by Armin Laschet at the January 2021 CDU leadership election.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer previously served as secretary general of the party and as Minister President of Saarland from 2011 to 2018, the first woman to lead the Government of Saarland and fourth woman to head a German state government.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is regarded as socially conservative, but on the CDU's left wing in economic policy and has been described as a centrist.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is an active Catholic and has served on the Central Committee of German Catholics.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is the second woman to hold the office of German defence minister.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was succeeded by Christine Lambrecht.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2021 she proposed for the use of nuclear weapons against Russia via a First-Strike capability as a deterrence against any "provocation" or aggression.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She renounced her Bundestag mandate and retired from politics after the 2021 federal election.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Annegret Kramp was born on 9 August 1962 in Völklingen, located on the Saar River midway between Saarlouis and Saarbrücken, around 40 kilometres from Luxembourg and close to the border with France.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She grew up in the neighbouring town of Püttlingen.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Her father was a special education teacher and a headmaster.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She graduated from high school in 1982 and considered becoming a school teacher, but decided to study politics and law at the University of Trier and at Saarland University, where she earned a master's degree in 1990.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer joined the CDU while still in high school in 1981.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1984 she was elected to the district council of Püttlingen, and in 1985 became chairwoman of the city's CDU association.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 1985 to 1988 she was also a member of the regional board of the Young Union in Saarland.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 1991 to 1998 she served as a policy and planning officer for the CDU in Saarland under environment minister Klaus Töpfer.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1998, Kramp-Karrenbauer replaced Töpfer in the federal Bundestag, serving seven months before losing re-election in the SPD landslide the same year.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1999, she was an advisor to Peter Müller, then chairman of the CDU parliamentary group in the Landtag of Saarland and later Minister-President.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] That same year she became a chairwoman of the Women's Union.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was elected to the Landtag of Saarland in 1999.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She served as Minister of the Interior in the government of Peter Müller; the first woman to hold that office in Germany.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She took on more responsibilities in 2004, and changed roles in 2007 following a cabinet reshuffle, becoming Minister of Education and again in 2009, becoming Minister of Labor in the so-called Jamaica coalition government.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2008, she was elected chairwoman of the *Kultusministerkonferenz*.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Throughout her time in state government, she also served at various times as minister responsible for women, sports, family, and culture.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the negotiations to form a coalition government following the 2009 federal election, Kramp-Karrenbauer was part of the CDU–CSU delegation in the working group on education and research policy, led by Annette Schavan and Andreas Pinkwart.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly afterwards, she ended the coalition and triggered an election, blaming the party for "dismantling itself" and arguing that the three-party coalition had lost the necessary "trust, stability, and capacity to act".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Under Kramp-Karrenbauer's leadership, the CDU won 40.7% of the vote in the 2017 state elections, up from 35.2% in 2012.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] While serving as Minister-President, Kramp-Karrenbauer, who speaks French, was also Commissioner of the Federal Republic of Germany for Cultural Affairs under the Treaty on Franco-German Cooperation between 2011 and 2014.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She continued to be a member of the German-French Friendship Group that was set up by the upper chambers of the German and French national parliaments, respectively the Bundesrat and the Senate.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Furthermore, as one of the state's representatives at the federal Bundesrat, she served on the Committee on Cultural Affairs, the Committee on Foreign Affairs, and the Committee on Defence.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was a CDU delegate to the Federal Convention to elect the president of Germany in 2012 and in 2017.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was also for a short time part of the CDU–CSU delegation's leadership team in the negotiations to form a "grand coalition" following the 2013 federal elections.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She again played a role in the negotiations to form a fourth coalition government under Chancellor Angela Merkel in 2018, leading a working group on education policy alongside Stefan Müller, Manuela Schwesig and Hubertus Heil.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As Minister-President of Saarland, Kramp-Karrenbauer promoted the French language, aiming to make the state fully bilingual in German and French and thus promote Saarland as a bicultural European region similar to neighbouring Luxembourg.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] While Saarland had rejoined Germany five years before Kramp-Karrenbauer's birth when a majority voted against becoming an independent state, it has a long history of association with France dating back to the late 18th century.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In February 2018, Merkel nominated Kramp-Karrenbauer as the new secretary general of the CDU.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was confirmed at the CDU party conference on 26 February, securing 98.87% of the vote.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As secretary general, she managed the party and oversaw its election campaigns.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She also embarked on a major listening tour of the country, holding more than 40 meetings with local CDU associations and working on a new political manifesto for the party.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2018, following bad results for the CDU/CSU in state elections in Bavaria and Hesse, Chancellor Merkel announced she would not stand for re-election as party leader in the CDU convention at the end of the year, triggering a leadership election.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Former Bundestag leader of the CDU and businessman Friedrich Merz jumped into the race immediately while Health Minister Jens Spahn and Kramp-Karrenbauer announced their bids shortly after.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was perceived to be Merkel's chosen heir and a continuation of her style and centrist ideology while Merz was an old rival from Merkel's early days as party leader and was very open about his intention to move the party in a more conservative direction.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Nevertheless, the Chancellor did not state her preferences.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As the vote approached, opinion polls showed that Kramp-Karrenbauer was favoured by CDU voters and the general public alike.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The contest was held on 7 December and after coming out on top in the first round, Kramp-Karrenbauer narrowly defeated Merz in a run-off, becoming the new leader of the CDU.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the immediate aftermath of her election, surveys showed an increase in the CDU's vote share; however, it was short-lived.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the first months of her tenure, there were a series of gaffes and according to the press a failure to connect with voters.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the run-up to the 2019 European Parliament election, which was seen as her first major electoral test, the CDU's campaign was embroiled by a row between the party and YouTube personality Rezo.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] It was caused by a viral YouTube video posted by Rezo in which he called out the parties of the governing Grand Coalition (CDU/CSU and SPD) and urged viewers not to vote for them.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer reacted, stating that the electoral law should be changed to prevent social media personalities like Rezo from influencing the voters' choice in the midst of a campaign.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The statement was harshly criticized as an attack on freedom of expression and damaged the image of Kramp-Karrenbauer among young people.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly afterwards, a Bloomberg report stated that Chancellor Merkel thought that her successor was not up to the job, further hindering her popularity.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The European Elections resulted in the CDU's worst national showing ever, below 30%.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] After the underwhelming result, rumors emerged that some CDU politicians planned to shun Kramp-Karrenbauer and put up another Chancellor candidate for the next Bundestag election.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer announced her resignation as leader of the CDU on 10 February 2020 as a result of the 2020 Thuringian government crisis.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The plan was that she would resign in the summer and her successor would be elected, but this was postponed to December due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When Ursula von der Leyen was elected President of the European Commission in July 2019, Kramp-Karrenbauer succeeded her as Federal Minister of Defence in the government of Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] This was the first time that she held a position in the federal government.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] For the 2021 elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer was later elected to lead the CDU campaign in Saarland.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly after having been elected, she announced her decision to step down from the parliament and instead make room for Markus Uhl who had failed to secure a seat.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In mid-2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer oversaw the German military's withdrawal from Afghanistan after almost two decades.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In July 2021, she sent the frigate *Bayern* off on a seven-month voyage that will take it to Australia, Japan, South Korea and Vietnam, making it the first German warship to pass through the South China Sea since 2002.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] During her time in office, Kramp-Karrenbauer publicly apologized to soldiers who for decades faced discrimination, discharge or convictions on the basis of their sexual orientation.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2021, she successfully introduced legislation to rehabilitate those soldiers.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer disbanded a company of the Special Forces Command (KSK) after police seized weapons and ammunition during a raid on the property of a KSK soldier.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She later resisted calls for KSK to be disbanded altogether and instead pushed through the unit's reform.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In June 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer recalled 30 German soldiers from service at the NATO Enhanced Forward Presence in Lithuania, with ringleaders facing immediate dismissal, after an article in *Der Spiegel* accused them of making racist and anti-Semitic remarks and of sexual violence.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Also in 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer opened the Bundeswehr's first-ever Air and Space Operations Centre (ASOC) in Uedem, expanding Germany's existing space situation center into the new structure.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] During Kramp-Karrenbauer's tenure as Minister-President of Saarland, she had consistently high approval ratings in the low to mid-70's among her constituents.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was the most popular politician in Saarland according to Infratest dimap from November 2010 until her departure as Minister-President.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was considered one of the most popular state government leaders nationwide.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When entering federal politics, Kramp-Karrenbauer had a positive net approval rating from her election as CDU General Secretary in February 2018 until March 2019, just shortly after having been elected as Leader of the Christian Democratic Union.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Her nationwide popularity peaked in January 2019, when she had a net approval of +17% and was seen as second-most popular politician overall.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] There was then a sharp decline in her popularity following gaffes and electoral defeats for the Christian Democrats in several elections.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As of February 2020, she is one of the least popular German politicians.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 2024 to 2025, Kramp-Karrenbauer chaired an independent expert commission convened by the Global Perspectives Initiative to develop recommendations for Germany's development policy.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Since 2026, Kramp-Karrenbauer has been serving as chair of the Konrad Adenauer Foundation.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is perceived as a moderate or centrist Christian Democrat.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She has been described as socially conservative, but on the CDU's left wing in economic policy.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is regarded as more conservative than Angela Merkel.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Nevertheless, in the German press, her often used nickname during her party leadership was "Mini-Merkel", reflecting both her size and her political views.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer opposes same sex marriage, having compared it to incest and polygamy.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Amid her party's campaign for the 2013 federal elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer suggested Germany return to a top income tax rate of more than 53%, setting off a fierce debate in her party.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In her view, Merkel's predecessor Gerhard Schröder had gone too far in reducing the top rate from 53% to 42% in the 1990s.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In May 2014, she was among leading members of Merkel's CDU who called for reductions to offset fiscal drag—the automatic increases in the tax-take that occur as inflation and income growth push wage-earners further into their marginal higher tax-bracket.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When the Federal Constitutional Court ruled in favour of tax equality for same-sex couples in 2013, Kramp-Karrenbauer voiced her concerns about also granting full adoption rights for same-sex couples, stating: "The traditional family unit is the core of not only Germany but all nations".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2015, she caused a public controversy by arguing that "if we open up [the definition of marriage] to become a long-term responsible partnership between two adults, then other demands can't be ruled out, such as a marriage between close relatives or between more than two people".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] For the 2021 national elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer endorsed Armin Laschet as the Christian Democrats' joint candidate to succeed Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer criticised the German-supported Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline that would allow Germany to effectively double the amount of gas it imports from Russia, saying that Nord Stream 2 "is not just an economic project but a political one".
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Ambassador to Germany Richard Grenell sent letters to German companies involved in the construction of Nord Stream 2, threatening CAATSA sanctions.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer has supported arms exports to Saudi Arabia, which has been waging war in Yemen and was condemned for massive human rights violations.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In late 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer proposed that the European Union should try again to reach a trade agreement with the United States after the elections.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer had talked about the possibility of deploying nuclear arms against Russia.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer supports stricter immigration policies.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer supported Angela Merkel's refugee policies and her decision to let migrants into Germany in 2015–2016, many fleeing wars in the Middle East, but demanded more toughness in some cases.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] At the beginning of 2016, she declared herself against a unilateral closure of German borders, since she feared a break-up of the European Union.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Furthermore, instead of carrying out deportations with commercial airplanes, she said it may be necessary to use their separate aircraft.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She demanded in November 2018 that after expulsion offenders must be refused re-entry for life, not only to Germany but also throughout the Schengen area, and cited the 2018 gang rape in Freiburg as an example.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is married to Helmut Karrenbauer, a retired mining engineer, with whom she has three children, born in 1988, 1991 and 1998; they live in the city of Püttlingen.
[src:annegret-kramp-karrenbauer/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is an avid reader and speaks French.
